text:
(1/6) good evening! iâ€™ve been busy behind the scenes of lilith rebellion, working on upgrading the structural foundations of my website.
.
i recently realized that i launched lilith rebellion (unintentionally) at the time of the inferior conjunction of venus and the sun, during venusâ€™ last retrograde period in the spring of 2017. the inferior conjunction is considered to be the birth place of each 584-day venus synodic cycle.
.
lilith rebellion began as a personal blog; an outlet for my love of astrology and the angst of my saturn return. however, it has gradually becomeâ€¦ something else. iâ€™m not entirely sure where it is headed, but as our current venus cycle begins to wrap up, it has become clear to me that my online platforms and branding needed an upgrade.ğŸŒŸ
.
we are just about to birth another venus synodic cycle â€“ beginning on october 26th when venus passes through a conjunction with the sun during venusâ€™ retrograde, which starts this friday. how exciting! truly, i think it is, even though i donâ€™t expect this scorpionic venusian deep dive to be easy.
.
aside from venus stationing retrograde on friday, we have mercury squaring pluto today along with the third quarter moon in cancer (tuesday), jupiter clearing its post-retrograde shadow in scorpio on saturday, and the sun conjunct ceres in libra on sunday.
.

text: earlier today i had a very real moment and shared it on my stories.  i made a complaint at a store i frequent about a man who kept making comments about how good i looked and it made me extremely uncomfortable way. it was very liberating, yet extremely overwhelming. so many emotions came over me. i was proud of myself for choosing to speak up about it because i never reported the person who drugged and raped me. i just let it go.  and i began to think of all the women who have come out to the public to speak up about what happened to them by celebrities and immediately felt soooo much empathy for them. people get up here on social media and drag women for speaking out years after the assault or inappropriate behavior happened. these same people can so easily dismiss us and our feelings because it doesn't make sense for them. but we have to be mindful of what it takes to even come forward and then the aftermath that happens when they do. it's extremely emotional and scary. so the next time we hear another story, be slow to make assumptions...listen to all the details...think about what it took for that woman or man to speak up...then make a conclusion. check out my live video to hear the whole story.

so now
our stories come softly forward.. with rage.

text:
these days, i feel that the world is going mad. but then i remember that it always was, and we are simply noticing more. * trigger warning *

dr. blasey ford's testimony speaks to this. the problem has always been there, under the surface. but we don't speak. out of fear. out of oppression. out of a lack of justice.

the courage shown by dr. blasey ford is astounding and inspiring. her testimony is raw: she does not want to be speaking these words, sharing her pain with the world. but she did. she spoke. even though her worst fears have been realized, in the form of death threats, hate mail, and the requirements of guards at her house, she spoke. and has held firm.

we need to tell our stories. but, sometimes, it is too painful to do this. sometimes, we can't. and that's okay. but, for those who can't, and for those who do, i am taking up this mission by writing the huntress.

this book deals with themes of sexual violence, sexism, and justice for survivors. the main character herself, aylin, is a survivor of sexual assault. the text is a teaser from my new #teasertuesday series, with excerpts from #thehuntress. this #teaser is in honour of dr. blasey ford's testimony, and the strength of survivors everywhere.

#christineblaseyford #blaseyford #supremecourt #stopkavanaugh #cancelkavanaugh #brettkavanaugh #istandwithher #whyididntreport #whyweneedfeminism #supportwomen #supportsurvivors #believesurvivors #metoo #sexualviolence

text: i think i saw it was national daughterâ€™s day the other day, and i started to compose a well thought out ode to my sweet girl. her fire spirit, her spunk, her big heart, the way she loves on animals and climbs every tree she sees. and then, the flurry of news this week with the kavanaugh hearings, at the same time iâ€™m counseling a friend through flashbacks of her own rape as a young girl, my own triggers decided to surface, the full moon craze amplified everything, and i broke down in tears wondering how to protect my girl from all of this ğŸ˜¥ i have so much thatâ€™s coming back up, i have so much to share, and itâ€™s all still so tender, even after two decades of growth and healing. and, at the heart of it all, is the fact that i am a mama. a mama to a daughter who will have to grow up in a world that historically has been powered by men. and a mama to four sons that will grow up in a world that is changing by the minute with the rise up of the divine feminine. we need both strong women and strong men that have each otherâ€™s back, supporting each other in love and equality. but, iâ€™ve not had the strength to be my most activist self this last week. iâ€™ve been a bit brain fogged and emotionally drained and just plain tired. iâ€™m writing out more of my story and there are so many layers and itâ€™s all so damn hard. way easier to just keep it tucked away, especially with having my oldest kids on social media now. but, my kids are the reason i need to share more of my story. so, that they can grow up in a world where they know they are safe to speak their minds, share their truths, and stand up to injustice and violence. and, so that they know their mama will do the same, for them, for others, for herself. the layers of trauma have a way of making us super strong as women, for all that weâ€™ve endured over time, and i am determined to pass that strength along to them, while also being a safe place to land when they arenâ€™t feeling their strongest. because the main thing we all need to remember in our healing journeys is that we need to feel all the feelings, process the pain, provide space for others to confide in, and be there when the pot of emotions boil over.(continued...)

text:
i don't understand when an adult over 40 says, "... he puts a lot of energy in understanding historical facts" in full acknowledgement that he really could care less about "historical facts" (bc historical facts just aren't hard to get a hold of, especially as the father to two school age toddlers) but also says, "i'm running for president and i'm not even going to try". i realize there is a growing stigma against american education and smart people, but come the fuck on
.

and i feel like there is this secret band of scared shitless white people looking out for other scared shirtless white people about brown people becoming the majority (...still not illegal for me to call meg newman a cunt, linda!) but really, if this guy is our next president trust the psychology will stay white and washed
.

and not to mention, you have to be pretty fucking lazy to not google information your unsure about. i'm telling you; the human brain can learn and unlearn absolutely anything if it's repeated enough. just try. we have enough accessable information to create artificial intelligence. that should be embarrassing. it's not ...which should be embarrassing
.

and because i know white mediocrity is an actual thing (white people can't understand the parameters of democracy and white people came up with democracy, so it's not shocking that it was only mandated in 1953 that all **presidents** should "most likely" have at least one college degree) it's proven oddly threatening to white people that privately identify with mediocrity ...dont blame me, just *go out and learn something*, bc this is just the tip of my research and it's certainly not stopping bc angry over nothing white people are still angry over nothing
.

and btw, do you know what you had to be to be like, a pharaoh? math and science enough to build buildings that stand today, left to cause white americans to wonder "if aliens made those things" - we are being duped by the lurid fable of "premicy"; superiority is in fact mediocrity, ladies and gentlemen. we are a very dignified people, we just had uneducated fucks running the government ... history tends to repeat itself

this was the first fairytale poem i wrote that started all the others. something that always bothered me about fairytales when i wrote this was how much we expect moral perfection from princesses. they always sacrificed themselves ultimately to prove their goodness. i wanted to read about girls making mistakes, committing very human error, being vengeful and finding hard won lessons in it all. instead all i  saw was sacrifice after sacrifice - in the original little mermaid she actually chooses to drown herself over killing the prince. it ingrained this idea in my head that women must be flawless, we cannot make any mistakes, not even mistakes to learn from. i strived for perfection for years, and hated myself for succumbing to any remotely negative human emotion. i wish someone had told me when i was young that itâ€™s okay to feel angry, and jealous and hurt and sad. thatâ€™s why i want to read my daughter flawed fairytales. thatâ€™s why i wrote fierce fairytales. .
.
.
edit: by the way, please donâ€™t come to my posts and tell me how much you hate aggressive women and how women and survivors being warriors makes you uncomfortable because women and survivors should only be soft and fragile and kind. women can be anything they want to be and so can survivors. you do not get to judge how anyone survives their trauma. this isnâ€™t even a radical feminist notion. it is literally common sense.
.
.
.
you can buy fierce fairytales from the link in my bio. #nikitagill #fiercefairytales #poetry

text:
fragile, please |
the kumiko panels for the bar arrived a few weeks ago from japan. i was going to post about their design, creation, and journey across the ocean; but instead, these words fell from my fingertips.
- - - 
we post it on boxes and cases
bound for worlds across the oceans
hoping they will be handled with care
fragile

within this shell is a work of art
labored over for countless hours
if you drop this it may shatter
fragile

as people, we seem to be stuck
standing with dignity
counting on decency so
fragile

human yet treated as lesser beings
than objects of glass, ceramic, or wood
our concept of self is
fragile

so please, donâ€™t crowd or touch without permission
for the tape holding it all together may snap
exposing the soul within that is still
fragile, please.
.
.
.

text:
this is important for ppl to understand. rape is rarely falsified and when it is 50% of those times it's a charge brought on by parents.the odds of a man actually going to jail for a rape are slim, much less an innocent man. 
so coming from someone who is in the 60% of women who have not filed a report, i'm asking that you consider listening to her. because the moment she's shut out by you, the dispatcher or some other influence she likely to hold on to her trauma.

society and victims bare responsibility in creating a system where accusations can be made without threatening anyone's safety. #metoo

text:
i feel like i am going to vomit. i am so fucking frustrated. 
let me tell you.

i am a victim of sexual assault. it happened during my freshman year in college. i believe i was drugged. the only reason i remember the year is because of the holiday season and that the campus was empty. 
what i do not remember:
1) the exact date
2) everyone who was at the party
3) the room i was assaulted in

i do and will always remember:
1) his name
2) his voice
3) when i said no

i am sick to my stomach because we have the president mocking a victim of sexual assault. no one seems to understand that when you are assaulted, you don't and can't remember the small details. you are traumatized. you have ptsd. you wake up a completely different person. you wake up unrecognizable to yourself, and spend hours in front of the mirror trying to figure out who you are.

how has the assault affected me?

obviously, everyone experiences things differently. i will say that, even to this day, being naked or wearing revealing clothing is extremely difficult for me. trust is an issue. i got into boxing and muay thai to be able to defend myself. if i am in a client meeting or surrounded by men, i run through scenarios in my mind about how i can get out of the room. this may sound insane, but it is my reality. 2 years or 40 years doesn't make the pain and trauma any less. 1 beer or 6 beers doesn't make the reality of assault any less. hearing trump mock dr. ford today just....it fucking hurt. sexual assault is real, it destroys, and we need to aggressively punish those who are active participants. 
so thanks, president trump, for reminding us; even though it is up us to spend years on rehabilitation and thousands of dollars on therapy, that regardless of the efforts we take to heal and come forward with the truth, that we are still liars and deserve to be assaulted...and that no one should believe us.

#rant #metoo #whyididntreportit #believewomen #kavano

text:
@copowerment - â€œ#men ask why #women are so pissed off. #jacksonkatz, a prominent social #researcher, illustrates why.  he's done it with hundreds of audiences: "i draw a line down the middle of a chalkboard, sketching a male symbol on one side and a female symbol on the other.
then i ask just the men: what steps do you guys take, on a daily basis, to prevent yourselves from being #sexuallyassaulted? at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally, a young a guy will raise his hand and say, 'i stay out of prison.' this is typically followed by another moment of laughter, before someone finally raises his hand and soberly states, 'nothing. i don't think about it.'
then i ask the women the same question. what steps do you take on a daily basis to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? women throughout the audience immediately start raising their hands. as the men sit in stunned silence, the women recount safety precautions they take as part of their daily routine.
hold my keys as a potential weapon. look in the back seat of the car before getting in. carry a cell phone. don't go jogging at night. lock all the windows when i sleep, even on hot summer nights. be careful not to drink too much. don't put my drink down and come back to it; make sure i see it being poured. own a big dog. carry mace or pepper spray. have an unlisted phone number. have a man's voice on my answering machine. park in well-lit areas. don't use parking garages. don't get on elevators with only one man, or with a group of men. vary my route home from work. watch what i wear. don't use highway rest areas. use a home alarm system. don't wear headphones when jogging. avoid forests or wooded areas, even in the daytime. don't take a first-floor apartment. go out in groups. own a firearm. meet men on first dates in public places. make sure to have a car or cab fare. don't make eye contact with men on the street....â€ #metoo #timesup â€• jackson katz, the macho paradox https://m.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-macho-paradox-jackson-katz/1122988065?

text:
if you think talking politics is â€œbad for business,â€ you must not understand what kind of business we are in.

in this business, the personal is the professional.

we live in a consumer driven world, where women dominate buying power. 
whatâ€™s good for women canâ€™t be bad for business. period.

women control over $20 trillion in worldwide spending.

women drive 70-80% of all consumer purchasing, through a combination of buying power and influence.

we have the power of the purse. have you seen our handbag collections?

so if youâ€™re wondering whether or not itâ€™s good for business to speak up, know this... itâ€™s not about politics.

itâ€™s not about whether we believe dr. ford.

itâ€™s about whether we care.

itâ€™s about whether we tell our stories in this moment when we have a real chance at people believing us.

itâ€™s about whether we take this opportunity to create a safer and more honest world for our daughters, nieces, granddaughters, sisters, friends, mothers, grandmothers â€” and ourselves because itâ€™s not too late.

itâ€™s about truth and integrity and equality.

nothing else.

we serve women, those identifying as women, those who feel safer in female spaces, so yeah, we care.

we give womxn the space to tell the truth and be seen, heard and believed, so yeah, we care.

we teach womxn how to turn their deepest pain into their greatest purpose and use their life stories to do it, so we care.

text:
#inktober day 2: the prompt for today was tranquil, and i was having a really hard time with it, since tranquil is not something i often feel, especially as of late. so i went with the opposite of tranquil. 
with the #kavanaughhearings and all of the political, patriarchal bullshit that is happening, i've been reliving a lot of experiences i'd really rather not relive again ever, and feeling a lot of the things i'd really rather not feel again ever. among all the hurt, shame, belittlement, disrespect, there's a lot of anger. so much fucking anger. how many times do we have to relive our trauma? how many times do we have to explain our collective grief? how many times do we have to say it? how many times do we have to fucking say it? 
#art #metoo #believewomen #believesurvivors #stopkavanaugh #resist
name: Jenn Angell

text:
thoughts-
the dating world is some kind of strange to me. as someone who is new to being single and never dated much because i was in one relationship that was 17 years long, another 1 year and one more that was a year and a half. that's all of my adult and adolescent life spent in relationships. so i may not know all that well what single is, but i do know what a real bond and what a real relationship is. to me the healthy thing after a relationship concludes is to spend time getting to know yourself again, love your own company, enjoy the things that you like to do at your own time and pace with friends and family. make goals and create obligations to yourself again. heal from any feelings of the past so that nothing carries over to the future. basically, time and self love. modern day dating however is mind boggling to me. these days everything is fast tracked with a swipe right, which is fine, i've done that... but the concept of really getting to know people and forming real bonds is rare. superficial and surface level communications via texts are now replacing real and getting confused with actually getting to know someone. with that being said- i'm not up to nor even about to play the "cool girl" role that is so popular in dating these days. if my stating that i'm not up to having sex with someone because i'm not ready causes a guy to stop speaking to me- guess what, i'm cool with that even if its contrary to what's acceptable by current standards. if i'm not up for cuddling and exchanging sexy pictures before we've even had a dinner date and sincerely gotten to know each other and that upsets someone- i'm all good with that. if my pace is too slow for anyone - we're better off as friends if anything at all. if ignoring texts that ask me to cuddle, sleep over, send a pic, talk explicitly, or just demand my time when i barely know you, offends you- that's okay with me too. it's okay to stand firm in who you are and what you want and need. this is a topic that's talked about alot in private these days but ya know what- someone needs to say it out loud. your choices are okay. it's okay to be your own kind of beautiful. 
#canyallhearmeintheback

text:
1. permission to be courageous to heal â€œi console myself with the fact that very young, and these events were unprecedented. women having to defend the most personal aspect of themselves, not even in court, but in the capitol building, on tv, and before the most powerful men in the world, had simply never happened. at that age and time in my life, i was not equipped with the permission and grit to allow my dignity, my sexuality or any violations to me to be strewn before the public. i am grateful that i never encountered what those women experienced. i know for a fact that i would have folded and walked away, never having the courage to stand up for myself.â€ more on the blog at: http://www.coachiyabo.com/possibilities-from-collective-trauma-to-collective-healing/

text:
i am about to begin posting screen-caps from my banned web pages and discuss my own personal experiences  with discrimination and harassment that led to attacks on my artwork.  however related, i am not comfortable with categorizing this as a #metoo moment .  the experiences that women have had and continue to have as part of our culture deserves its own unique focus free of tangents.

and yet, i do think my experiences as a gay man and a queer artist stand in relation to the me too movement--hence my hashtag #metootoo

text:
because i was in the marine corps.  i was only a lance corporal.  at the time i did not even know who did it.  i was not drunk.  but maybe i should have stayed down the lit path.  maybe i should not have taken the shortest way back to my tent. 
_
i felt ashamed.  i was scared to admit it.  i was scared it would happen again.  i was scared that it would end my time in the marine corps.  my life was threatened.  we were in another country.  i was still in shock.  my voice was taken from me.  because i felt no one would believe me.  something was taken from me and even though it is was not my fault, i felt the shame that it was. 
_
so it happened and i lived for 20 years not speaking about it.  but just because it was not reported, or talked about does not take my voice away from me saying that it happened, or when i decide the time is nowâ€¦..it diminishes what happened. 
_
you do not get to question why a woman chooses to not talk about, report it, tell her story.  but men seem to think they have that right, to give there opinion, to talk shit about, or to even question that validity of what the woman is talking about.  it will ruin his future.  he canâ€™t handle being in jail.  boys will be boys.  but did you say no?  his hand was over my mouth the entire time, so no could not be articulatedâ€¦.well then it is isnâ€™t rape. 
_
when a woman talks about what happened to them, they relive the trauma.  they relive the smells, the voices, words that were spoken, or the deafening silence, sounds, everything.  it stops you in your tracks.  and then after all those feelings come back up, you have to figure out a way to pick yourself back up, and carry on. 
_
every day. 
_
i see you.  i hear you.  i believe you. â€¢

text:
coffee shop chats: college students share their perspectives on the #kavanaugh hearing and the #metoo movement with vaughn hillyard of nbc. 
it was incredible to take part in something that gave us, as students, a voice. this really emphasized to me how important this generation is for the future. some are voting for the first time. some are just now opening up to the world of politics and social issues. some still turn a blind eye. what matters is understanding our common goal: to make progress as a nation and as human beings. to my generation: speak out! do not be afraid to form your own opinions and participate. vote! determine what you believe is wrong and right. keep humanity at the root of it. history is being written now.

text:
the power of social media... it seems every time i really think i shouldn't upload a particular video onto our youtube channel... the response (when i do) is overwhelming and so very relatable.  today's video for example... i was umming and ahhing about whether or not i should upload it... because we're currently living in our mini van and travelling australia while documenting our #vanlife adventures and it doesn't fall into that category.... because it might offend people or i'll get attacked from the cowardly keyboard warriors.... because i too have been seduced by the media and our cultural perversion to celebrating artificial beauty... or because i didn't think people would hear the message i was trying to articulate..... every time i doubt my videos.... people respond with their stories, their vulnerabilities and their truth.

itâ€™s not often that i weigh in on current events but i feel i canâ€™t stay silent after the comments made today by the president of the united states
.
â€œitâ€™s a very scary time for young men in america, where you can be guilty of something you may not be guilty ofâ€. when asked if he had a message for women his reply was â€œwomen are doing greatâ€
.
really? it is estimated that one in three women will experience sexual assault in their adult life.  sexual violence is prevalent.  the hashtag #metoo gave a personal face to the numbers.  itâ€™s one thing to hear that 1 in 3 are survivors. itâ€™s another thing to see that they are your friends, your neighbours, your relatives, your teachers
.
every survivor copes differently.  some women (and men) have chosen to tell their stories in detail when they are coming forward.  others are simply saying #metoo, without any more explanation. still others donâ€™t feel they want to go public.  there is no right or wrong way to survive sexual trauma
.

.
a fox news commentator said, â€œwomen who donâ€™t come forward are part of the problemâ€. no sir....you are. .
#supportsurvivors #metoo #bravery #compassion #solidarity #believe

text:
8 year old girl: mama, what is that picture about?
me: well, what do you see? 
8 year old girl: it looks like the church is trying to make the girl be quiet.
me: yes, yes, my girl. thatâ€™s exactly it.

in order to get to this level of violence though, we need to start with the underpinnings â€“ the implicit messages that become the air we breathe, inhaling and exhaling until the lines are blurred and self-doubt is the norm. the implicit messages that groom so many of us into becoming complicit with the culture of sexual violence towards females are like a layer of skin, so we think itâ€™s who we really are. 
this is where we begin.

i invite you to read the rest of â€œpart 1â€ of whatâ€™s sure to be a series on rape culture, sexuality, women and the evangelical church.

text:
breaking: potus mocked dr. ford at a rally in mississippi tuesday night, before intimating she belongs to a group of "really evil people" set out to destroy other people's lives ... like supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh. 
donald trump was bitching about due process tuesday, but just hours later made a mockery of his fbi investigation by essentially calling out dr. christine blasey ford as a fraud.
trump was egged on by his mississippi supporters, as he repeatedly made fun of ford's testimony about being sexually assaulted by kavanaugh ... specifically her claim that she only had one beer at the party where it allegedly took place.
trump's point -- we think -- is ford can't remember many details about the alleged incident.
earlier in the day, trump bemoaned what he says has become the marching orders in the #metoo movement -- guilty until proven innocent.
he apparently believes it's okay to short-circuit the legal process -- in this case the fbi investigation he authorized -- and just jump to the conclusion ford must be a liar. #trump #brettkavanaugh #daminorityreport

text: a few months ago, my mom sent me a link to a youtube video of christina aguileraâ€™s new song â€œfall in lineâ€ and said it made her think of me. at first in my head i was like, â€œwait arenâ€™t i the one that usually plays songs for you?â€ and â€œitâ€™s been years since iâ€™ve listened to christina (not including her old stuff because letâ€™s be honest, that shit does not get old) so what about this song makes her think of me?â€ i hadnâ€™t even finished the song before i let my mom know how unreal and unbelievable that song was. within an hour, we had tickets to her concert at radio city in nyc. this concert happens to be tomorrow and i get to hear this song live. it is extremely relevant to me while also being incredibly relevant to everything that is scattered across all the news and all of the social media. i listened to the song on repeat for days and eventually felt inspiration for a totally new and somewhat terrifying (ok very terrifying) photography project based off of her raw and real lyrics-one that not only will help with my own healing, but one that i hope can reach someone else. i am so used to photographing landscapes and nature so here is to something completely new. i have no idea when my first real image for the project will happen, but itâ€™s about time that i start... because i have a fire in my veins.âœ¨ #photography #photograph #selfportrait #christinaaguilera #xtina #music #lyrics #inspiration #healing #metoo #wearblack #blackandwhite #blackandwhitephotography #portraitphotography #portraitmode #photooftheday #storysisterhood #photographyproject #timesup #innocent #innocence #strength #fire #truth #relevant #currentevents #ibelieveher #listen #women #womenempowerment @sophiabush

text:
â€¢this shit happens all the time! not just with politicians and celebrities... but in our neighborhoods, schools, churches, and most often in our own families! â€¢
âœ–ï¸
â€¢i donâ€™t know care if the victim is a man or a woman, a child or a drug addict... i choose to believe them when they come forward; no matter how long it took them to speak!â€¢
âœ–ï¸

text:
hi ig friends and family.  october is domestic violence awareness month, and though this is not a subject most are eager to talk about, as a survivor, i am driven to do everything in my power to shed light over this traumatic epidemic and give hope to those still suffering. 
domestic violence is not only bruises, black eyes, or broken limbs. it's repeated yelling, belittling, shaming, and constantly stripping someone of their self-esteem and dignity.  it's stalking, sexual assault, persistent unwanted contact, and any behavior from a partner/spouse that makes someone feel threatened or fearful of suffering physical or psychological harm.

please keep in contact with any family members or friends whom you suspect are being victimized.  notice if they have withdrawn from normal activities.  pay attention to their behavior and if they become highly defensive when asked about their partner.  watch for changes in their personality outside of normal mood swings, a decreased desire to communicate with family, or poor performance on the job or at school. 
domestic violence victims live in constant fear and are often too ashamed or afraid to come forward, as their abuser may have threatened to hurt a family member or other significant person in their lives.  but if we all do our part to check on our loved ones, pay attention to the warning signs, and make the commitment to not be a by-stander, but instead someone who speaks out and gets help for the victim, we can help save lives within our families, communities, and beyond.  thank youğŸ’œ #domesticviolenceawareness #breakthesilence #protect #women #men #family #friend #wife #mother #daughter #sister #coworker #metoo #imasurvivor

text:

text: when you're young, they tell you if anyone hurts you, if anyone touches you, tell someone. and that's that. a black and white problem and solution. and then so many women move on to to perpetually live in this gray fog. but what if it's someone who you really love, and who really loves you? what if it's your boss and you can't afford to lose this job? what if you were too young to really even understand what was happening? what if you had a few too many drinks and now feel responsible? what if you were drugged and literally have no clue what happened? what if you already told someone and nothing happened? what if you have seen so many women in the media go through hell and you figure "this" just has to be better than "that"? and then there's the fear of being labeled as anything besides "strong". i may not know you, but i know you're strong as #@%! for enduring that. for carrying that secret with you every day. for trying to find it in you to forgive so you can return to peace. for your daily efforts to move forward and make a life that feels tarnished actually feel brand new. i may not know you, but i know you're the strongest person in any room. and i'm here for you â¤

text:
do you agree? president trump said tuesday the controversy surrounding brett kavaughâ€™s nomination to the supreme court shows it is a â€œscary time for young men.â€
"it is a very scary time for young men in america, when you can be guilty of something you may not be guilty of," trump told reporters on the south lawn before leaving the white house.
trump said kavanaugh has been treated unfairly as multiple women have come forward to accuse the federal judge of sexual misconduct. the fbi is investigating the allegations, delaying a senate confirmation vote.
"it's a very scary situation where you're guilty until proven innocent," the president said. "that is a very, very difficult standard."
trump's comments are likely to fuel the firestorm surrounding kavanaugh's nomination and renew questions about his attitude toward the "me too" movement. #men #metoo #kavanaugh #stopkavanaugh #supremecourt #sexualassualt #women #womensrights #highschool #college #judge #trump #senate #congress #usa #womensequalityday #womensrights #conservative

text:
the 11th hour
.
when it comes to our rights, itâ€™s the 11th hour for women. we wonâ€™t even have had the right to vote for 100 years until 2020. the right to choose has only been possible since 1973. whatâ€™s important is to realize that this isnâ€™t just about the right to choose whether to carry an unwanted pregnancy to term. this is about the very fundamental right to have control over our own bodies.
.
right now, with the kavanaugh nomination, women are freaked and rightly so. not only will he vote to overturn roe vs wade, this man is a revengeful bully and he clearly has no real respect for women. anyone with any degree of understanding of human behavior can see that clearly. this is a man who needs to be in control and feels entitled be so. if this man gets on the supreme court heâ€™ll not be impartial, especially when it comes to issues impacting women. he will rule to wield his power because he can. heâ€™ll rule to get revenge. i wasnâ€™t happy with the gorsuch nomination as heâ€™s in the pockets of big business; but the thought of kavanaugh as an arbiter of womenâ€™s rights is truly frightening.
.
itâ€™s the 11th hour for womenâ€™s reproductive rights. itâ€™s time we keep calling our senators and try to keep this clock from reaching the darkness of midnight. @blueravenartist

text:
letâ€™s go ahead and talk about the elephant in the #news right now. .
letâ€™s talk about it because so many women have kept quiet, including myself, for a long time.
.
as a woman, iâ€™m disgusted and infuriated by the stupid jokes that i hear about how i should be making sandwiches instead of remodeling homes. iâ€™m even more disgusted when homeowners refuse to work with me because, â€œwhat could a woman possibly know about doing a manâ€™s job?â€ or i must not have a brain- or i get the, â€œoh thatâ€™s cute. you think you can climb a roof.â€ - why yes. yes i do, and i can also carry my own ladder ğŸ˜®
.
i donâ€™t need a man telling me what to do, i donâ€™t need a manâ€™s opinion to feel confident or capable, and i certainly donâ€™t need a man condescendingly telling me that iâ€™m not good enough simply because i have boobs. these opinions are trash. .
i know my own worth. .
when a woman is #violated in a way that strips her of her dignity, she is left feeling ashamed. she even will find blame in her own actions. and she carries a fear of being criticized or publicly put on display for all of the world to judge. (imagine that.) we see people crucified everyday in the media and internet - buried by public opinion even with factual evidence, their story is smothered with false narratives. .
our tv shows, music, politicians and public figures are no role models in todayâ€™s society and i question how many parents take an active role in teaching general respect and common courtesy to their children. .
on the flip side iâ€™ve seen women expose parts of themselves publicly that only god should know about. so to be fair, if iâ€™m going to hold the men of this world to a standard, then i will also hold my fellow sister to one as well. use common sense and good judgement. learn how to protect yourself so you are less likely to become a #victim. surround yourself with people who lift you up and support you. and if you are #assaulted - my heart goes out to you - donâ€™t let what happened to you define who you are. i hope you have the #courage to tell your story so that others may follow. #sexualassault #womenempowerment #abuse #outwithit #metoo #women #survivor

text:
"the limits of our stories are the limits of our lives. our words should open up the world, not close it off. our words should include all people, not trap them in cages.

i see every story, every word as a struggle of memory against forgetting." - lyz lenz

i read @lyzlenz 's article, "why writing matters in the age of despair," this summer and it's one of the most moving and poignant pieces i've ever read, not only as a writer, but also as a woman, as a mother. in the midst of the #metoo movement, as we are finally becoming brave enough, feeling safe enough, to share our stories, many are still trying to silence us. but sharing our stories shouldn't only be validating, it should be liberating and uniting. in all of the stories finally bursting through into the mainstream, not just #metoo stories, but stories of tragic injustice - stories of residential schools, stories of missing and murdered indigenous women, stories of systemic racism that kills and imprisons people of colour, stories of abuses suffered by people and children with physical or mental illnesses, stories of people struggling with mental illness - these stories are heartbreaking, but they're necessary. we must not remain complicit and silent, we must not be allowed to forget, we must use our words to open up the world, whether we're writers or not. our stories are our power, our stories matter.

read lenz's full piece here (link temporarily in profile): https://therumpus.net/2018/07/why-writing-matters-in-the-age-of-despair/

text: the #metoo movement - the anti-bullying movement and any relationship where someone is denying their own hurtful or cruel actions share many dynamics - the most important one because if you donâ€™t move past this â€œpointâ€ - no real change can happen - it keeps children, adults, men and women  quiet or â€œconfusedâ€ or shamed for their legitimate feelings - they are real bc the person is expressing them - the one being accused of bullying or assault is not the one that decides if their actions are abusive or cruel - the person who has the events happen decides for themselves - so when you get gaslit - you learn to stuff the feelings and build resentment and sadness and isolation.  the  callous behavior and attitude is how the bully or abuser or simply the person who is being an insensitive asshole - will try to flip the script (consciously or unconsciously) when you or the person saying they are being mistreated or abused speaks up for what they feel is careless, mean, rude, assaultive or thoughtless words or actions the perpetrator will scream loudly of the victims â€œsensitivityâ€ and that its â€œnot that badâ€ or â€œdidnâ€™t happenâ€ this is â€œgaslightingâ€. what i have learned over the years in my practice and in my personal life is we should believe and listen and care when someone shares their emotional pain.  #shrinkland #drmaddog #speakup #standup #makechange #stopkavanaugh

text:
day two @birdsongbrooklyn #nourishedpostpartumchallenge // food // â€œa full fridge makes me feel safeâ€ âœ¨when my first daughter was born, after 3 days of labor, i was served my deep craving for a sushi salmon roll and a cold beer. yes, it was delicious. it was also probably one of the only consciously planned for meals for several months to come. during pregnancy i ate well, and a lot. it was the first time in my life i had a genuine desire to eat multiple meals a day- my body would not let me skip a meal. and as a former actress who struggled with body image and disordered eating (and straight up periods of eating disorders) i found this to be very healing. 
cut to postpartum. i was hungry. all the time. my baby breastfed every 15-60 24 hours a day for 6+ months. i was a mess. and yet, there was still this societal voice that rewarded my hunger. i had gained over 50lbs in my healthy pregnancy, and even in some of the spiritually minded health based books i read that seemed "too much". needless to say i was both tortured by and reveled in the hunger. 
i've been thinking about consumption and birthing bodies. the assault and abuse and misuse of power i have experienced in life all stem from the idea that my body is for male consumption. in week three postpartum an ex of mine emailed me to "congratulate me" on my baby. he attached a picture of me half naked on a beach at age 18 and "joked" that he was sure i'd be back to looking like this before too long. 
we had a complicated past and hurt each other and also loved each other and i have held back speaking on this publicly because i know him in much more nuance than villain. but what he did was so completely abusive. so wildly inappropriate and disrespectful on every level. he invaded my sacred postpartum space to flaunt a picture of me (dude, this pic was pre-iphone, i'm talking developed at a pharmacy days so that creeper had to scan that shit...) and try to control, what he knew, was my deep feelings surrounding my body and self worth. 
i do not get less mad about this as time goes on. i get way more mad as time goes on. people regularly do not eat enough in postpartum because (contâ€™d ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼ in comments)
name: Laura Interlandi

text:
what we don't realize is that there many instances of abuse daily but they are not publicized or covered on the news because they happen a lot and it would be impossible to cover. what we have to do is speak about abuse. it is so taboo that is why it continues to be prevalent among us. whether assault or abuse, we have to acknowledge that domestic violence is a problem and it happens more than not.

text:
mercedes gallego (@gallegom) was the only female spanish journalist to live among american troops in iraq during the 2003 invasion of the country. as an embedded war reporter stationed with the u.s. first marine division, she uncovered sexual abuse riddled within the military. her career later led her to publish several award winning stories that placed her on an international pedestal for journalism. she also published the non-fiction book "mÃ¡s allÃ¡ de la batalla: una corresponsal de guerra en irak" ("beyond the battle: a war correspondent in iraq") and coauthored the 2009 award-winning documentary "rape in the ranks: the enemy within". mercedes is currently the u.s. bureau chief for vocento media group. 
covering some of the worldâ€™s most appalling, beautiful and breaking stories for the daily news outlet, @elcorreo_com - she joined @bradshowlive to share a particular story assignment that emotionally struck a chord with her: the 2010 haiti earthquake.

highlighting how millions of haitians endured such catastrophe - gallego told @bernstein_brad that â€œi have been to many countries, but the one i treasured the most was haiti because the people have such a strong spirit despite all that they go through.â€ in the face of an apocalyptic natural disaster that killed friends, families and ravaged communities, she described a silver lining aura that penetrated the atmosphere. â€œthey (haitians) hold no resentment towards life or others. that was such a learning experience for me that i keep it close to my heart,â€ she said of her coverage in haiti. 
check out brad's full interview, and watch brad show live monday through friday from 5:30-7:30 p.m. est. on youtube (link in bio)

text:
today in our class at tufts, kris and i talked with our students about countless generations of racial violence, and how the burden of proof is always on the target of violence, to produce evidence. whether or not evidence is produced, we then say it didn't happen. we have ignored multiple generations of genocide and systemic abuse on bodies of color, and female bodies, and bodies of "other" religious identities, those that do not conform to dominant norms of gender, and so much more. in this system, body memories are used as evidence, and simultaneously denied. so for targets (a term i can embrace, as opposed to "victims"), we are asked to give testimony over and over again, and not believed. but we can visible-ize, make visible, what has been rendered invisible. that is our task: to do this first for ourselves, and then to the world. today, our theme is tending to the bodily archive of memory and trauma. it's not a linear thing- as in, we do our work in therapy and yoga and then no longer have the intimate connection with the experience of our bodies not belonging to us. we testify to our bodies, to the way memory resonates in a non-linear way, to the ways in which images, sensations, and memories unfold like origami birds, opening still more, taking flight where they will. today, i call upon us to connect with nature, to touch the damp earth of her body, to sense her memories of intrusion, commodificatiion, and assault and to draw nourishment from her eternal wise patience in making her voice known. get in water: an ocean, lake, river, or your shower or bath. do some connective tissue work and self-massage using sesame or almond oil. abide in what is. you are, indeed, as big and vast as the earth, able to hold all, with a vision that extends beyond any individual lifetime. more new stuff on igtv and insta stories. love to all. ğŸ’š

*

text:
"fuck you to metoo":
thank you, jeff flake. finally, someone from the spineless, soulless republican party connected to his conscience.
but please, letâ€™s not get carried away here. yes, there is a pause, a reprieve from this madness, but it took two traumatized women -one who was revealing her assault for the first time and whose mother watched her do it live on tv, no less- standing in an elevator pleading: â€œlook at me when iâ€™m talking to you! youâ€™re telling me that my assault doesnâ€™t matter. that what happened to me doesnâ€™t matter!â€ at flake for him to do what could and should have been done before the hearing was ever conducted: require further investigation in to the sexual assault allegations. i guess you could call him heroic or you can just say he was the only republican willing not to say â€œfuck youâ€ to #metoo!
the hearing was in groucho marxâ€™s words: â€œa mockery of a travesty of a sham.â€
the idea that the republicans were interested in really listening to blasey ford was a joke. how could you watch her tell her story, a story that one in four women in this country could tell, and not find her credible-at least credible enough to want more information, to not â€œplow through.â€
in my last piece â€œall mixed up and nowhere to go,â€ i ended with the following, regarding the build up to the hearingâ€
yes, letâ€™s â€œplow through,â€ â€œunfazed and determinedâ€ as we have our way with ms blasey ford, as we stifle her right to have witnesses (hold a hand over her mouth), while we bully and demean her, blame her, question the validity of her experience, praise the guy for showing restraint, question her capacity to identify her assaulter. in other words, letâ€™s treat her the same way kavanaugh did...

text:
i didnâ€™t want to share this incident when the me too movement started. i donâ€™t know why. i think it might be that i just didnâ€™t want to relive it or bring any part of it up to the surface. and also because i wasnâ€™t actually raped during this incident. i shared this incident with a friend last night after hearing a blythe baird slam poem about sexual assault, and i shared it with a friend today. i know he didnâ€™t actually rape me and so much worse has happened to people, and i also acknowledge that i exist in a social position where i can call 911 for help without a second thought about it. that is not a privilege everyone shares. in the moment i 100% thought he was going to rape me (and possibly kill me afterward) and it was extremely traumatizing. i hadnâ€™t realized how much space it took up in me. i was 20 years old. #metoo
side note, because we are always so concerned with what female bodies are wearing when they are assaulted: i was wearing baggy restaurant slacks, a baggy fast food polo, and a hoodie. fuck you.

text:
since the #metoo movement started, i have seen countless amazing women (and men too) come forward about this issue. to which i also continue to say that i am sorry if i ever made anyone feel uncomfortable like this. but while it seems like the majority are simply going up in arms just to pick a fight, it is nice to see that there are those who are trying to gather all the facts.

this article from #thewashingtonpost perhaps shows it best. since the #kavanaugh accusations began a common counter-arguement has been "why now?" "why wait 30+ years?" granted, the timing is a little off but people fail to see the real reasonings. the reason they came forward now is because survivors finally feel safe enough to do so, that they aren't alone.

when i found out my sister was attacked, a pit grew in my stomach like nothing i had every experienced. when i found out it was our own father that attacked her, and that pit started to spit fire. my exact words were "the police better get to him before i do." i was going to kill him, but that was only because of the guilt i had for not being able to protect my family. i'm not a father, but i get it. often i would be asked if he ever did anything to me, to which i never could answer fully since much of back then was blocked out in my head up until recently. big chunks are still missing but i believe that my father did do something to me.

my words to the survivors are this, you don't have to handle this alone. yes, it will hurt your loved ones to find out but having that secret come out later on only makes it worse. and trust me, the secret always comes out. you won't be thought of as anything less and coming forward isn't a weakness.

#timesup #truth #realstory #reachout #timeheals #believesurvivors #believewomen #sexualassault #survivors #awareness #yourenotalone #christineblaseyford #stopkavanaugh #survivor

text:
just finished #scummanifesto by valerie solanas - i went in thinking 'oh this will be a psychotic lullaby' but actually the anger towards the behaviour of alphamale toxic masculinity and it's very witty put-down of that type of man as an abboration (read trump) - solanas is almost a superhero for the #metoo movement - of course she isn't as this 1967 manifesto quickly turns into some prequel to a sci-fi epic of an automated machine society where money, government and men are abolished and females live for eternity without disease or the need to reproduce (something that can be achieved in a few weeks - she promises) - i like the anger and ironic dismantling of an ugly, destructive male world where war and lack of personality is man's compensation for covering up that they'd rather be women - apparently gay men are the most inoffensive type as they've toned down there maleness - she has no understanding of transness, but knows all about the women 'the daddies girls' that keep the bastards in place - in all it reads like a parody of a feminist by a rabid republican wanting to show the world the bogiewoman is real! 
solanas wrote this before going out and shooting andy warhol so i guess you can take her manifesto about as seriously as that... also avital ronell's lengthy introductory essay is just a mass of complex twisted verbiage that again read like a parody of a gender studies professor! going as far as to say people's names were magnets for behaviour 
still a fascinating read and i wish solanas had written it in 2018 where i guess it would be weinstein, trump or kavannah getting the bullet...

text:
i can't even express how angry and upset this post makes me feel.  as a female athletic therapist who works predominantly with male sports teams i have dealt with my fair share of crude and vulgar comments.  thankfully it is very rarely from my own athletes but i have had my own team coaches, parents, opposing team coaches, players, fans and officials all make comments anywhere from "oh the boys are so lucky to have a pretty girl working with them.  i bet they love that" to "oh i bet i know why those boys like to come get treatment from you so often..." .
it really just boggles my mind that in such a "progressive" society, and with all that is going on with the #metoo movement that this crap still keeps coming up over and over again!
ğŸ’¥
do you realize how hard it is to be a female in an all male environment?
ğŸ’¥
do you realize how often we have to brush off vulgar comments and pretend that they don't bother us? ğŸ’¥
do you realize that we work just as hard, if not harder than our male counterparts to get the job done and ensure our athletes get the best possible care they can?
ğŸ’¥
can you not get it through your heads that we do not work in these environments just so we can be "surrounded by hot men" all day. that we are simply incredibly passionate about what we do and want to work to the highest level we can?!
ğŸ’¥
to male athletes who have female staff (or really any men who have any sort of interaction with women in the work place) - please squash this kind of talk the second you hear it and let people know that it's not ok!  stand up for the women in your life because we struggle with this daily!
ğŸ’¥
and ladies, although we can't avoid all of this crap entirely, we also have a responsibility to tell people when they are being inappropriate.  a lot of the times i believe the comments (these ones on the sportsnet post excluded!) are not intended to be offensive, the people are just oblivious to how it comes across.  we don't have to attack them for it, but bring awareness to what they said and and how it made you feel.
ğŸ’¥
so to all you female ats out there, stay strong and keep paving the way. we are all in this together âœŠ
name: Jessie Wyllie, CAT(C)

text:
seriously... on a societal level right now. 
from last year ... a man responding to a post about women needing to be heard and acknowledged. men "holding space". annnnd then my response to him. 
him, speaking to a woman:
"when i have to read this stuff one more time, i go nuts. see her, really see her, hold space for her, wholeheartedly realize her beauty, for the first time.... please, stop it and come back to earth. i promise you women, if you stop glorifying yourself in such a ridiculous way, life will become a lot easier and its a lot more attractive to men.
as i have said: i have to read this stuff again... ... you didnt write about humans in general, you wrote this: "when you truly see her, hear her, know her, you can become aware of her beauty and power." sounds to me, like you were talking about woman, you know, that glorifying stuff i have mentioned before. 
so, my statement stays: come back to earth, men are still waiting here for some grounded woman." my response:

annnnnnd we have a winner. lol. 
of course you're triggered. you don't want to show up like that for a woman. "men are waiting for a grounded woman" = "men are waiting for a man". lol 
you. do. not. get. to. decide. how. a. woman. should. be. 
you get to enjoy them or not, and right now you're not enjoying them. 
you can blame that on them all you want. but guys like me that love chaos? we'll be off enjoying them and making a new world where your attitude becomes extinct." i am not wanting to judge this guy. he is doing the best he can. everyone is. my job is to point out that what he wants is impossible or unsatisfying. if you are looking for a woman who does not have an emotional reality that makes you "uncomfortable" or desires that are "otherwordly" you are wanting a woman that is one of three things. 
1) weak
2) dead inside 
3) a lying manipulator 
i have plenty of things to say to women who want "finished" men too. 
but this all too common agreed upon bypassing of the feminine's emotional reality (and their involvement with it) is the denial of divine feminine identity and it has to stop. 
#metoo #whyididntreportit #meditation #emotionalintelligence #love #healing

text:
three years ago i walked away from a 5 1/2 year career in education.

it hasn't been a walk in the park, but i have grown closer to myself on this entrpreneurial journey.

i left becuse i didn't believe in the capitalist exploitation of the students i was serving.

i started my first online business, cagefreelmt.com in protest of the financial exploitation of many spa workers.

i helped bodyworkers, somatic practioners, massage therapists and estheticians create businesses to free themselves from the stranglehold of working for spa chains, that exploited their bodies for profit.

i recently founded transformea in protest of us (entrepreneurs, creatives, coaches, founders) exploiting our own bodies for profit.

i want to see a world where women balance healthy living, healthy relationships and running businesses that thrive.

i believe we can build wellness into our operations, strategy, business models and product development when we are intentional about how we design our businesses.

i believe business can be a tool for healing, for fighting injustices and for as much profit as we desire.

want to learn more - click the link in my bio

text: if you are familiar with the critically acclaimed tv show â€œmad men,â€ then you know about their fervent attention to historical detail. the creators got many things right on that show but there was one thing they got wrong â€“ betty draper being a graduate of bryn mawr college. writing for the atlantic, benjamin schwartz argues, â€œby far the brainiest of the seven sisters â€“ cussed, straight-backed, high-minded, and feminists (its students preferred the ph.d to the mrs.) â€“ bryn mawr was probably the least likely college that betty draper, given to such non-u genteelisms as â€˜passed away,â€™ would have attended.â€ bryn mawr has never been a breeding ground for suburban housewives destined to suffer from ennui. one look at their actual alumni (not their fictional one) and you can easily see how empowering the college has been for thousands of women. from artists to engineers, pulitzer to nobel prize winners, bryn mawr has been the place women go when they want to receive the same elite education as men. #feminism #womenshistory #brynmawrcollege #brynmawr #sevensisters #madmen #bettydraper #ushistory #katharinehepburn #woodrowwilson #mcareythomas #metoo #womenscollege #nettiestevens #marktwain

text: tuesday is #red4ed  and we are again wearing red to show our support of teachers and fighting for public education. red, the color of passion, love, anger, danger.  seeing red goes along with blind rage. is anger a bad emotion?  no. all emotions have a job and a message to deliver. angerâ€™s job is to tell us we want a change. anger is a call to action. anger can keep us alive. it connects us to our survival ğŸ§ . anger is always a shield for sadness and/or fear. think about it.  the challenge is to get the message without reacting to the survival surge of emotions, adrenaline and energy that come along with anger. it puts us in a state of fight flight or freeze aka feigned death. it can make our child look like the enemy. if we can hear the message - press the pause button, we can make the choice not to react - and instead respond in a helpful way.  we need to feel safe to reconnect our brain. iâ€™m seeing a lot of red these days. i am getting many messages from anger telling me i want/need lots of things to change.  i am listening to the message and trying to breathe and effectively respond. breathe in love, breathe out fear. #chooselove #chooselove #chooselove #ibelieveher #iloveteachers #supportpubliceducation #metoo #believesurvivors #survivornotvictim #selfregulation #selfregulationtools #teachersmakeadifference #peacefulparenting #peacefulparent #parentcoach #streetart #loveisloveğŸŒˆ #lgbtfamilies #votingmatters #gentleprenting #sel4ca #nonviolentparenting #attachedparenting #emotionalintelligence

text:
for the last two and a half weeks i have been traveling around the uk with my sweetheart. we have explored and fallen in love with scotland, and are at our final stop in england before heading off on the boat east. we are sad to be leaving and also reveling in all we have shared these last weeks.

i could say a lot about the trip but itâ€™s not whatâ€™s most present for me. i approach instagram posts like i would a conversation with a friend, it feels easy for me to be transparent and explicit about my joy and my grief. the last month has been wrought with both. iâ€™ve felt my emotions swinging on a pendulum continuously throughout each day. often waking up and feeling unsure if iâ€™m happy or sad or somewhere in between. my eyes feel heavy from crying everyday, and my cheeks are also feeling the ear to ear grinning. itâ€™s not comfortable but iâ€™m trying to be present first and foremost. nightmares have been a normal and anxiety is starting to lead to exhaustion.

i donâ€™t live a â€˜normalâ€™ life and i never really have. itâ€™s my choice and a blessing in many ways, but it also feels like an added challenge when i feel off-kilter to identify whatâ€™s throwing me off. so much is typically out of balance from the outside perspective that i could give reason to any number of things for why i feel uneasy, depressed, an achy gut, achy body, tear filled and confused. 
much of what iâ€™m feeling these days feels visceral. i canâ€™t explain my feelings, i just know them; many are fleeting. they are hard to trust. fear and anxiety are some challenging suitors who have persuasive and alluring offerings. they draw me in much faster than the invitation from elation and contentment. i have to convince myself to breath more deeply and take in the beauty. 
this last year has been a lot of this. maybe itâ€™s the political times, maybe itâ€™s a mending heart, maybe itâ€™s my saturn return, maybe itâ€™s my nature, and maybe itâ€™s going to pass. i do feel confident itâ€™s a bit of all of the above. thank you as always for witnessing me on this journey and for sharing yourself. 
every person i encounter is feeling the challenges of these times. may we continue to find avenues of connection and support.

text:
the purple purse challenge is back! each october during domestic violence awareness month, the allstate foundation holds a national online, peer-to-peer fundraising program called the purple purse challenge to bring awareness to the issue of economic abuse in domestic violence cases. economics are the major reason people stay in abusive relationships. collectively, the organizations raised $4.4 million to help the 300 organizations!

the challenge in 2018 will run from today through october 31st. tennis champion serena williams is again the spokeswoman for the purple purse challenge in 2018 and has designed the purple purse. the center for women and families has participated yearly in the purple purse challenge since 2015. last year we raised and won $74,000 and placed 9th nationally. can you help us raise even more this year?! follow the link in bio for more info.

text: to my 17 year old self - today you got the phone call you have been waiting 7 years for. today the police department called you and told you they looked into your sexual assault report from 7 years ago and realized something didn't add up, someone messed up your case. they apologized, something you thought you would never hear. they told you they were going to reopen your case, they were going to help you, get you a victim advocate, that they cared, that they heard you. it may have taken going to the media to start this journey, but you are finally going to get the answers you deserve. i hope more than anything you get the justice you deserve, but just know this is a battle that i will never stop fighting for us.

â€œtwo and a half men was one of the best things that ever happened to me.â€ jennifer taylor refuses to knock the bawdy, perpetually clever 30-minute sitcom that launched her into the living rooms of 15 million viewers over two seasons. as no-nonsense brunette bombshell chelsea melini, she loved freelance jingle writer and constant philanderer charlie harper â€œfor who he was despite some of his crap.â€ before joining two and a half menâ€™s sixth season in 2008, the sole female player on her 10th grade football team had spent eight financially uncertain years slogging through occasional guest turns in movies and tv series. compounded by a poor economy and writersâ€™ and actorsâ€™ strikes, taylor was on the precipice of selling her modest los angeles home and moving back to miami to pursue a teaching career with her electrician husband, son, and incoming bundle of joy.  taylor was as low as any person could go, face down on the floor begging to god.................in her most expansive interview, charlie sheenâ€™s tv fiancÃ© talks #metoo, bad auditions, intuition, awkwardness, health, and god. you can google â€œheart to heart with â€˜two and a half menâ€™ outsider jennifer taylorâ€ for 40 photos and videos as well as the full interview. itâ€™s my best story of the year.....................https://medium.com/@jeremylr/heart-to-heart-with-two-and-a-half-men-outsider-jennifer-taylor-187052e1d1

text:
i am domestic violence survivor.
i created this brand to empower women and others to believe in themselves and to conquer all of your fears.
i travel near and far to inspire others victims that their is hope! 
you can make it.
you can survive
you can live.
i was beaten over 80% of my body and i didn't tell anyone for  20 years and for the portection of my family.
but through  god..prayers.. and the love of my children and mother & father.  i made it!
to bring  full closure  and peace within my soul..
i ha to forgive a dead man in order for me to live.
every purchase helps others and their families and journey.  vondor.
named after 
my son
ser(von)te
my daughter
(dor)othy
vondor ..a unique taste of elegance.

take 1 sip & take your power back!.;@copywright

text:
are you still feeling it? do you find yourself trying to shove yourself through the week and it feels like trying to put the biscuits back in the busted can?

you're not alone. it's okay to take some time to simply be right now. 
be gentle with yourself,  be gentle with others, feel it all, speak it all if it's healing to do so and please remember,  it's not okay to tell someone else how to feel. 
it's okay if people are overly defensive right now, it's okay if people are highly sensitive... this is a time of collective growth, let's hold space for it. 
listen to your body and your heart.

when you have time and a safe space let your anger and pain come and sit with you in catharsis. open up conversation, ask your heart to tell you what really hurts, be open to whatever comes up, let it wash over and through you.  it doesn't have to stay, it's been with you long enough, some parts of it will remain, the bulk doesn't need to though. 
also, if working through it looks like saying a massive "fuck you, i'm not going to keep hurting!" and doubling down on your goals etc,  do that.  whatever feels good is the right thing as long as you're not hurting people who are doing their best to get through this too.

sending so much love.  if you think a healing session could help you further process, please pm me, i do one-offs in times like these to help move this energy. .
.
.
.
.

now imagine being sexually assaulted, a moment you'd feel most vulnerableâ€”would you ever forget that? no. it haunts you.

since watching videos of the committee testimonials and reading statements about the sexual assault allegations, iâ€™ve thought about the piece i wrote that details what happened in a bathroom of a high-rise apartment during a house party in 2014. i've considered finally sending this article to the guyâ€™s girlfriend whom i've noticed he's been dating for a couple years. i occasionally look the guy up on facebook (weâ€™re not friends) to stare at his face and wonder if he has also pinned his girlfriend's face against the cold bathroom counter while unzipping his pants or held her up by her neck against the wall with her feet dangling off the floor, yelling "yes or no?!" i shouldâ€™ve called the cops then and made an official reportâ€”not left in shame and fear. but i doubted myself, felt at fault, wanted to forget it all happened.

only lately, because of the #metoo movement, have i realized so many other women have done the same thing:

been silenced.... click link in bio to read todayâ€™s blog post! â€”> sabrinamust.com/dr-christine-blasey-ford-brett-kavanaugh-handmaids-tale-metoo-movement/ .

text:
i have never been more worried about being a female coming into herself in this day and age. men understand this isnâ€™t to cut you down or say you have a lack of struggles. i know there are fantastic honest men out there. iâ€™m dating one.
.
.
we live in a society where there is danger in all we do.
.
â€¢ donâ€™t walk alone at night .
.
â€¢ watch your drink when out with friends .
.
â€¢ meet first dates in a public place and make sure people know where youâ€™re going .
.
â€¢ i wanted to go for a walk on a beautiful trail but couldnâ€™t because all i could think about is a young girl who went out for a run and never returned because she told a guy to go away .
.

â€¢ i have my story in the #metoo movement but refuse to share it and if you spend two minutes on social media youâ€™ll understand why .
.
â€¢ we question if women were really assaulted when they donâ€™t come forward but shame them and tell them we donâ€™t believe them when we do . .
â€¢ we are terrified that our rights are going to be taken from us at any minute. .
.
i feel like weâ€™ve stepped back years. i canâ€™t even believe my mind some of the things we have to go through, things all humans have to go through, in 2018. this isnâ€™t a political post this is a â€œwe need to do better postâ€. as a society we need to practice empathy, compassion, minding our own damn business, acceptance of differences. what saddens me is that this cry will go unheard. however, if it reaches you in some way then just take one, just one, small step on having a positive impact on the change in society. thatâ€™s all i ask from you.

text:
ok so when i was in junior year i was at one of my best friends house. there was three of us, all best friends, hanging out and having fun at the pool. out of all things that day, i definitely didnt expect to break down into tears in the hot tub. i donâ€™t remember what it was now but something triggered me and all the memories i had of being sexually assaulted as a very young child bubbled back up. i wont go into much detail but it happened in the middle of the night, while on vacation with family and people i, at the age, of around 4 thought were to be trusted. 
i had completely repressed that for about 13ish years. 
sometime later when it exploded out of me through tears, she was asking why i had waited this long to say anything. she started calling family and investigating. she thought i was trying to take attention off other things. she didnt believe me. 
when i was in second grade in the aftercare program, a boy grabbed me by my groin behind a tree during our playground time and i froze.
i didnt do anything and i didnt tell anyone. i was scared. 
i repressed this for years. it bubbled up for the first time watching dr. fords testimony.

text:
now is the time for men to show up and take responsibility for changing the state of masculinity in our world. and there's a big difference between men who are showing up to the challenge and the men who aren't. .

those who are committed to showing up will hold themselves accountable for missing the mark. they grow and become better men as a result of being accountable and their positive impact will be felt by those around them. it is chiefly their willingness to hold themselves accountable for their failures while still continually striving to improve which sets them apart from men who don't show up. .

because the men who don't show up will always find someone or something to blame for why they are the way they are. these men are skilled at deflecting their responsibility to become better men, and are known for making excuses for their harmful behavior. .

there is a lot more to it but we would like to hear from men who are choosing to show up, struggling or succeeding, how you are investing your time and energy to become a better man and how you are ensuring your accountability. and for women who want to encourage men to show up please do. ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¾ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼ğŸ‘‡ .

text:
there's no wrong way to have a body, there's nothing you have to change for your body to be perfect or ideal. 
the idea of a "perfect body" we all have to want, worship, starve for and mistreat our bodies for is not just ridiculous because the are millions of different bodies that simply because of the way they are cannot have the "ideal body" diet culture imposed on us, this idea is also extremely harmful for mental and physical health. it. has. to. stop. 
let's all accept the fact that all bodies are good bodies! let's stop the exceedingly damaging message that there's just one "good" "perfect" or "ideal" body! .
.
.

text:
according to one historian, â€œfew scholars have viewed the relationships of enslaved men and free white women through the lens of sexual abuse in part because of gendered assumptions about sexual power." this is in keeping with both the standard feminist conceptualization of rape as a tool of patriarchal oppression, as well as the traditional (un-feminist) notion of women as too weak, emotionally and physically, to commit serious crimes, let alone sexual abuse, and the idea that men cannot be raped.
*
*
however, it is becoming increasingly clear that women, too, are capable of committing sexual offenses and using sex as a means of domination and control. indeed, there is considerable documentation of white women coercing black men into having sex. according to captain richard j. hinton, an abolitionist commander in the civil war, â€œi have never found a bright-looking colored man, whose confidences i have won, who has not told me of instances where he has been compelled, either by his mistress, or by white women of the same class, to have connection with them." one former slave told hinton that his mistress ordered him to sleep with her after her husband died. these are just two examples of the many stories abolitionists like hinton told to prove the immorality of slaveholding.
*
*
'sexual relations between elite white women and enslaved men in the antebellum south: a socio-historical analysis' by j.m. allain (2013)
*
*
#whitewomen #massaswife #rape #blackmen #slaverydays #rapeculture #metoo #whitewomenlie #whitefeminism

ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
â€œshe was raped at the age of 8. her rapist was found guilty, but spent only one day in jail. shortly after he was released, he was murdered. because of this, she became mute for almost 5 years, believing her "voice killed him." "i killed him, that man, because i told his name. i thought i would never speak again, because my voice would kill anyone ..." her name was marguerite ann johnson. later in life, she would change her name . . . to maya angelou.

during this time, this period of suffering, this period of shame and guilt, this period of silence that she "developed her extraordinary memory, her love for books and literature, and her ability to listen and observe the world around her." a teacher and friend of the family helped angelou speak again, introducing her to the world of books with authors such as charles dickens and william shakespeare.

when she finally did speak, she said she had a lot to say.

maya angelou became a voice for women, a voice for the black community, garnering respect and admiration for her honesty.

she would say, "there is no agony like bearing an untold story inside of you." angelou was challenged by her friend, author james baldwin, to write an autobiography, which became "i know why the caged bird sings". the book would be critically acclaimed, but banned in schools and libraries because of its honest depiction of rape.

when asked by an interviewer why she wrote about the experience, she indicated that she wanted to demonstrate the complexities of rape. she also wanted to prevent it from happening to someone else, so that anyone who had been raped might gain understanding and not blame herself for it.

she would also later write another book titled "letter to my daughter", which was dedicated to the daughter she never had but sees all around her.

in the book, she says, "you may not control all the events that happen to you, but you can decide not to be reduced by them."
#mayaangelou #metoo

text:
i stayed slient
i bore my pain, my loss, my betrayal.
i held my screams inside so long, they festered like an infection. 
an infection planted inside my body, my mind, my soul.
i began to rot.
oh not on the surface, deep, deep within, buried, soul broken, heart worn.
i mourned little michelle as if i had died. i mourned the last shreds of innocence i had.
i had to rise! rise and become my true self, my ancient self.
i had to rise and daily glue the shattered pieces of self back together, cracks of light shining through.
i did not speak out, instead i carried this festering infection with me always trying to heal it, cut it out, burn the cords that tied me to him.
each one of us has carried our pain, shame, fury. we have felt that even if we scream our story from the highest cliff, no one would believe us or care.
even as i pry the steel clamp of silence from my mouth, i fear.
i fear that my story, my truth will not matter to the world, to anyone but my loved ones.
i wanted to scream it from the highest cliff and yet i whispered it into the sea of our stories, our pain.
our ocean grows, and somehow through our shared pain, we grow, we release and we heal.
even as i am part of this revolution, i struggle with no one hearing my cries, until i see that each drop of rain is alone until it unites with the sea.
we are more powerful together! a drop of rain in a sea of pain!
we will not be silent any longer! we are brave! we are mighty! we are one!!#whyididntreport #metoo #metoomovement #believesurvivors #iwillnotbesilent
