text:
george balanchine famously said â€œballet is woman.â€ ___
with everything going on in the world, it seems strange today to use a quote from someone who, letâ€™s face it, would not have a job in the #metoo era. 
___
but ballet is indeed powerful. and it is woman. on a lot of levels. and itâ€™s world ballet day!! ___
i never feel more beautiful than when i am in ballet class. (especially when i was a teenage bunhead.) but ballet had also made me feel like a failure. itâ€™s hard not to have a love/hate relationship with an art form so grounded in beauty and aesthetics, but also artistry and expression. ballet teaches passion and discipline and dedication and perseverance and resilience and fierceness and softness and perfection and community and individuality and failure and strength and vulnerability. as contradictory as they are on the surface, those qualities all add up to power. 
___
especially today, as women are being questioned and challenged in our place in the world, i carry my ballerina self with grace and dignity, in every breath and every step i take. 
___
#worldballetday #beingadancer #classicpointeshoeshot #ballet #ballerina #bunhead #dancer #lifecoach #power #strength #vulnerability #resilence #pointeshoes #perfection #failure #lifelessons

text:
speaker announcement!! beckie masaki has been at this work for over 30 years and we are very honored to have her as a speaker at the #imready movement conference!
.
.
beckie masaki has worked in the field to end genderÂ­-based violence for over 30 years. in 1988, she coÂ­founded one of the first programs in the nation that could meet the language and cultural needs of asian survivors of domestic violence and trafficking, asian womenâ€™s shelter (aws) in san francisco, and served as the founding executive director for over twentyÂ­one years. beckie is a coÂ­founder and has been on staff of a national cultural resource center, asian pacific institute on genderÂ­ based violence. she is also a movementmaker in the move to end violence (mev), starting with the 2009 advisory group, first cohort, and currently coÂ­leads the communities/ building the power of the margins practice group as part of the mev alumni network, resonance. beckie has extensive experience in providing multilingual, multicultural services to domestic violence and trafficking survivors and their children, innovative program development,
prevention, community building, policy and institutional advocacy, training, technical assistance, and cultural change work. beckie is committed to make her best contribution to the movement for gender justice as part of a critical interconnected network of intergenerational, diverse leaders in a new era of shared leadership, shared power, and coÂ­creation. she is dedicated to work through an intersectional approach that builds the power of the margins and is marked by collective power, collaboration, creativity, and love.
.
.

text:
this card and art print seems so pertinent after last week. i tend to prefer to keep my thoughts and feelings fairly private and it takes me a long time to process them, so by the time i'm ready to say something, especially online, the window of relevancy has passed.
.
i was out of town last week for family reasons, so i'm just now catching up on the news of the supreme court hearings and it is painful to watch on so many levels.
.
dr. christine blasey ford is brave, because she told her story, and i cannot imagine how awful all of this has been for her. there are so many of us, who for various reasons, can't or won't tell our stories. "tell your story" isn't meant to be a directive. it's meant to be an encouragement to be yourself and to use your voice in the world. how you choose to do that is up to you.
.
i ask anyone who has not been a victim of sexual assault to understand that for every woman who speaks up, there are countless other women who are too afraid or simply don't want to share publicly. if you wonder why women are enraged by what we see on the news, it's because, at least in my case, it truly feels like we're being heard, but those in power are saying they donâ€™t care. and honestly, i might delete this post, because sharing this even feels too vulnerable. #metoo

text:
on the #drosrape, you're #notallmen faves out here accusing #blackfeminist of staying quiet about the rape because we coddle or protect white masculinity. asserting that we are only quick to outrage when the alleged perpetrator is a black man. i cannot even belive this is even a conversation we are having, once again, rapists are rapists. the only thing this conversation serves to do is defer and distruct us from having a conversation about the core of the issue, a child was raped. children continue to be raped.  women are raped. and they continue to be violated by men they trusted. by strangers. by bosses who hold jobs and their income at ransom. the class and race of the perpetrator is irrelevant to this conversation unless it leads us to ways to end this, otherwise keep quiet if you have nothing better to say. this is not a race war, it's a war against people's bodies and freedom. stop trolling. we are worried about our safety and you're once again making it about your ego. 
#metoo #menaretrash #genderbasefdviolence #violenceagainstchildren #violenceagainstchildren #johannesburg #southafricanblogger

text: #nojusticenoseat: women and survivors of sexual violence are furious at the nomination of brett kavanaugh to the supreme court of the united states. dr. christine blasey ford and other women have accused kavanaugh of sexual assault and his judicial record makes clear he cares only about the privileges of elite white men. if he becomes a justice on the supreme court, he will likely help to overturn roe v. wade and strip away the rights of women. activists gathered in flatiron district to demand that kavanaugh be punished for his crimes, not given a lifetime appointment in the highest court of the land. #believesurvivors #trustwomen #cancelkavanaugh #stopkavanaugh #kavanope #women #smashthepatriarchy #thefutureisfemale #pussygrabsback #neverthelessshepersisted #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #feminism  #intersectionalfeminism  #abortionrights  #womensrights #reproductiverights #womensrightsarehumanrights #nastywomen  #resisttrump  #impeachtrump #dumptrump #activistny #documentaryphotography #photojournalism #endrapeculture #stoprape

text:
read: this is a picture of my face
.
this is also a picture capturing a moment of relief after getting trapped by the heat on a 3 hour walk, alone, aimlessly seeking a remote beach in lagos, portugal
.
this is also a picture of me, topless, when i discovered the remote beach was also peppered with a few brave souls who also had to walk across treacherous rocks to get to this cove, who were also naked and half naked in this intimate setting
.
but what this is mostly a picture of is  a moment where i worked up the nerve to feel safe enough to be in my skin, alone, in another country. this moment was profound for me because of the way i learned, as a little girl, that my body was only ever the object of someone elseâ€™s desire, having little to do with my ability to choose how i see myself
.
this is also a picture of my refusal to let the voices in my head win as they shouted rape culture learnings like â€œyouâ€™re asking for trouble!â€ and â€œare you sure your towel is a safe enough distance from the men here?â€ and â€œnobody knows where you are, what if....â€ (fear even in broad daylight)
.
not to mention that this was a moment where i silenced the contradictory and self-deprecating voices which shouted â€œno oneâ€™s staring at you, so you are not beautifulâ€ and â€œyour boobs are too small to be topless.â€
.
womxn and mxn: this is a common narrative, yes? and we need to be sharing these experiences in order to dismantle them, yes? and, even more beautiful, is that i promise you, we can even live, truly live! we can honor our contradictions by observing these thoughts and feelings, (the â€œstuffâ€ which clouds our radiance) and then we can make choices to be gentle and open to the possibility to get free from the program
.
but we must do this together. you can look at my booty and acknowledge my story. i can choose to be free and ask you to respect my boundaries. this is the work. how are you contributing to shifting our cultural narrative to make space for all of this?
#traumaintegration #traumatranscendence #metoo #nomore #bodysafe #womensreality #mensreality #believeher #gratefulheart

text:
tiny hands and cigars, digital art, 2018. as a woman, i am sick and tired of being "represented" by these men with #tinyhandsandcigars . if we want the fourth wave of feminism to move forward, we need our elected and appointed leadership to respect women. this means an end to abusive behavior and sexual misconduct. this is not a war on men, it is a war on the terror that we as women experience every day. be mindful of how you cast your vote. make it your responsibility to remove narcissistic and authoritarian candidates from office. choose candidates who work from a place of love and compassion rather than power. what is a narcissist? a narcissist is someone who pursues love and/or wealth without concern for the effect his/her pursuit has on others.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
â–ªred wrathâ–ª
you knew that your touch would kill me, 
yet you didn't care. 
you were fingers of iron, 
pricking through my untouched skin, 
ruthless thorns that turned me into rivers of red. 
my soul hasn't stopped screaming since, 
the cries growing louder when the sun sets.
i won't mourn for the me that died that day, 
nor will i pity the empty shell that's left behind. 
the thing i can't deny, 
however, 
is that i'd rip the remnants of my wings out, 
just to drag you down to hell with me.
